The setup is complete. Here are the three steps to go from "server starts" to "agents are working":

---

## Step 1 — Create your `.env` with a real GitHub token

```powershell
Copy-Item c:\PowerShellGUI\agents\focalpoint-null\.env.example `
          c:\PowerShellGUI\agents\focalpoint-null\.env
```

Then edit [agents/focalpoint-null/.env](c:\PowerShellGUI\agents\focalpoint-null\.env.example) — the only line you **must** change:

```env
GITHUB_TOKEN=ghp_yourActualTokenHere     # needs read:models scope
PKI_MASTER_SECRET=some_32char_strong_secret_here
```

Get a token at [github.com/settings/tokens](https://github.com/settings/tokens) → **Fine-grained** or **Classic** → no special scopes needed for GitHub Models.

---

## Step 2 — Start the server

```powershell
Set-Location c:\PowerShellGUI\agents\focalpoint-null
C:/PowerShellGUI/.venv/Scripts/python.exe main.py
```

You'll see PKI bootstrap + "Server ready at http://0.0.0.0:8087" in the logs.

---

## Step 3 — Send a chat request

```powershell
# Health check
Invoke-RestMethod http://localhost:8087/health

# First real request
$body = @{ message = "Review the PowerShell GUI main script for security issues" } | ConvertTo-Json
Invoke-RestMethod -Method Post -Uri http://localhost:8087/chat `
    -ContentType "application/json" -Body $body
```

The request flows: **FocalPoint-null** → routes to **SecurityTriage** / **AgentReview** / **Code pipeline** based on content → response returns as JSON `{ "response": "..." }`.

---

**Quickest test without credentials** — send a message that only needs the orchestrator to respond (doesn't require a live LLM sub-agent round-trip):

```powershell
$body = @{ message = "hello" } | ConvertTo-Json
Invoke-RestMethod -Method Post -Uri http://localhost:8087/chat -ContentType "application/json" -Body $body
```

